Again, as many people do, you miss a main point of Moore's -an important finding, and exactly contrary to the anti-gun genre attributed to Moore's film:<br>
 Moore proves as a main tenet of his stance, that the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>number of guns</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in the us per-capita or in-toto has no correlation to the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>number of gun deaths</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
 Simply saying that the US has a lot of guns, and a lot of crimes with guns, isn't valid. The higher population in the US compared to the number of guns and crimes does not draw us to the conclusion that the nuumber of guns drives the number of gun crimes up.<br>
One of Moore's main conclusions is that the number of guns has nothing to do with the number of crimes. He says there is something deeper going on, something even more scary than guns. The US just is nutso, and there's an unhealthy cultural thing which makes some of us go off against each other.<br>
 Thus, many people (but not Moore himself in the movie) take it to mean that the poor dumb sheeple need to be protected from themselves, and since many sheeple are afraid of the nasty guns, they're a natural target for enacting involuntary rules on what the idiot citizens should have within hands' reach.<br>
<br>
Before you agree with the gun prohibition anyway, read again the stats I mentioned above:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:large;">*</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Vast majority of crimes do not involve a gun,<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:large;">*</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> vastly higher number of innocent law abiding and justified uses of guns to stop crimes than any number of gun-related deaths (Suicide, accident, or deliberate crime),<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:large;">*</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> vanishingly small number of private citizens using guns in defense causing collateral damage, Much smaller percentage than with police using guns, and causing collateral or regrettable damage or harm<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:large;">*</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> vanishingly small number of legally bought guns used unjustly (suicide, accident, or crime)<br>
<br>
and don't forget<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:large;">*</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> after gun prohibition passed in the UK or OZ, crime skyrocketed up, and even <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>gun crime</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> went up!<br>
Prohibition doesn't work! Anywhere, ever!<br>
<br>
I also like another statistic which goes against the idea that government agents are the only trustworthy ones to have guns:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:large;">*</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the number of innocent people killed worldwide by supposedly trustworthy and lawful government agents, is vastly higher than any number of unjust harm caused by guns in private hands -even discarding numbers of soldiers killed in wars!<br>
genocide or other stripping away of people's human rights is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> preceded by disarmament.<br>
<br>
Disarmament of civilians says -must mean to say- that people are inferior to and subservient to the government.<br>
Take it as swaggering american gun-nut hysteria, but I challenge anyone to prove that it does not necessrily mean a step away from increasing liberty<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="">&quot;Our legislators are not sufficiently apprized of the rightful limits of their power; that their true office is to declare and enforce only our natural rights and duties, and to take none of them from us.   <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Thomas Jefferson, Letter to F. W. Gilmer, 1816</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;The history of liberty is a history of limitation of government power, not the increase of it.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Woodrow Wilson</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Liberty has never come from the government. Liberty has always come from the subjects of it. The history of liberty is a history of resistance.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Woodrow Wilson</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Men by their constitution are naturally divided into two parties. 1. Those who fear and distrust the people, and wish to draw all powers from them into the hands of the higher classes.  2dly those who identify themselves with the people, have confidence in them, cherish and consider them as the most honest and safe, although not the most wise depository of the public interests.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Thomas Jefferson, Letter to H. Lee, 1824</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Guard with jealous attention the public liberty. Suspect every one who approaches that jewel. Unfortunately, nothing will preserve it but downright force. Whenever you give up that force, you are ruined.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Patrick Henry, 1788</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Gun control? It's the best thing you can do for crooks and gangsters.  I want you to have nothing.  If I'm a bad guy, I'm always gonna have a gun.   Safety locks?  You will pull the trigger with a lock on, and I'll pull the trigger.  We'll see who wins.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sammy &quot;the Bull&quot; Gravano (formerly of the Mafia) in a Vanity Fair interview.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;When the government fears the people, there is liberty. When the people fear the government, there is tyranny.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Thomas Jefferson</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Laws that forbid the carrying of arms...disarm only those who are neither inclined nor determined to commit crimes.... Such laws make things worse for the assaulted and better for the assailants; they serve rather to encourage than to prevent homicides, for an unarmed man may be attacked with greater confidence than an armed man.&quot;   <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>18th-century criminologist Cesare Beccaria in _On Crimes and Punishment_, 1764</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Taking my gun away because I might shoot someone is like cutting my tongue out because I might yell 'Fire' in a crowded movie theater.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Peter Venetoklis, 1994</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Good intentions will always be pleaded for every assumption of authority. It is hardly too strong to say that the Constitution was made to guard the people against the dangers of good intentions. There are men in all ages who mean to govern well, but they mean to govern. They promise to be good masters, but they mean to be masters.&quot;   <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Daniel Webster</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Concerning nonviolence: it is criminal to teach a man not to defend himself when he is the constant victim of brutal attacks. It is legal and lawful to own a shotgun or a rifle. We believe in obeying the law.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Malcolm X, 3/12/64</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I find the level of paranoia in US pro-gun rhetoric to be disturbing.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Indeed!<br>
